 gaming.\r\n\r\nOur organisation is extremely new and we are actively seeking feedback from gamers to make our services relevant to them. If you\'d like to take part, <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1SKbZJriGMKq6x2XRMsY5OxVeHyrqBzXinDZOUSW2udI/viewform\">please complete this short signup form</a>.\r\n\r\nHere\'s some of what are aiming to do to achieve our mission.\r\n<h3>Education</h3>\r\nWe aim to provide education to all parts of the gaming community on relevant topics in conjunction with other organisations and charities. This includes providing information to community leaders on how to achieve goals set for their communities and pastoral care for their community members. We also seek to provide information to parents and other interested persons on gaming.\r\n<h3>Support</h3>\r\nWe will stand up for the good that gamers do, and help to make it easier for them to continue this. We want to <a href=\"http://www.localhost/community\">bring people together</a> to enable useful dialogue with others on personal issues or on those affecting whole communities and provide easy access to professionals who can help.\r\n<h3>Fundraising</h3>\r\nWe will fundraise to continue our work and to support the work of other organisations that make a difference to gamers worldwide. We will also provide advice and help to other gaming communities looking to do the same for their own nominated charities.','What we do','','inherit','open','open','','57-revision-v1','','','2014-08-26 18:35:56','2014-08-26 18:35:56','',57,'http://localhost/2014/08/57-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(75,1,'2014-08-26 18:51:34','2014-08-26 18:51:34','Healing Over Time is\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2>Core beliefs</h2>\r\nTransparency\r\n\r\nEquality\r\n\r\nPassion\r\n<h2>Fundraising</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Organisation Structure</h2>\r\nHealing Over Time is applying to become a non-profit organisation within the United Kingdom. This allows us to minimise our expenditure whilst still being as productive as we possibly can be.\r\n\r\nEveryone supporting the organisation is a volunteer, and all staff members are passionate gamers.','Who we are?','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-08-26 18:51:34','2014-08-26 18:51:34','',23,'http://localhost/2014/08/23-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(76,1,'2014-08-27 22:32:13','2014-08-27 22:32:13','In the US alone, consumers spent over $4.6 billion on games and related accessories in the first quarter of 2014 <a title=\"NPD Group Post\" href=\"https://www.npd.com/wps/portal/npd/us/news/press-releases/npd-total-industry-consumer-spending-on-video-games-at-4-billion-for-q1-2014/\" target=\"_blank\">[1]</a>. Across Europe, 25% of all people play games at least once a week <a title=\"ISFE\" href=\"http://www.isfe.eu/industry-facts\" target=\"_blank\">[2]</a>. Despite this, gamers are frequently misrepresented. Whilst recent research shows a 48% of gamers are female, and 49% are over the age of 35 <a title=\"ESA 2014\" href=\"http://www.theesa.com/facts/pdfs/esa_ef_2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">[3]</a>, gamers are frequently considered to be predominately young males.\r\n\r\nIt\'s not just the outside world that has it wrong. Within the industry and the gaming community there are frequent frustrations about issues such as accessibility, anti-social behaviour and representation.\r\n\r\nDespite this, there is a lot of good going on in gaming. There\'s growing scientific evidence that playing games improves learning and raises self-esteem. There\'s plenty of anecdotal evidence that games can help families and friends stay in touch, as well as enabling people to cope with difficult times in their lives.\r\n\r\nThe benefits aren\'t just personal. In 2013, gamers raised over $11 million for Extra Life and Child\'s Play, with plenty of other fundraising campaigns for other charities. <strong>Gaming organisations such as guilds are often a first step t</strong>\r\n\r\nHealing Over Time is run by and for gamers, regardless of their experience level or physical location. We want to help gamers and gaming be the best it can be.\r\n\r\nWe do this by helping gamer communities to grow and aim high, enabling people to find the information they\'re seeking, tackling the hard topics and changing misconceptions about those who enjoy gaming.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Our Organisation</h2>\r\nHealing Over Time is applying to become a non-profit organisation within the United Kingdom. This allows us to minimise our expenditure whilst still being as productive as we possibly can be.\r\n\r\nEveryone running the organisation is a volunteer, and all staff members are passionate gamers.\r\n\r\nWe fundraise to continue and expand our work, and support other non-profit organisations and charities. Who we support changes over time and we will always be transparent about where your money goes.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Our History</h2>\r\nThe organisation has been borne from a number of gaming communities coming together with similar interests. In December 2012, the guild Mystic Spiral ran a 24 hour gaming marathon which raised $525 for Child\'s Play. In March 2014 the first Healing Over Time event took place, with 7 guilds coming together for a joint marathon which raised $6,456 for Child\'s Play, supported by industry partners including Green Man Gaming.\r\n\r\nFrom there we\'ve aimed higher and wider. We want to find others who share our vision and passion to build on what we\'ve done to see where we could go.','About Healing Over Time','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-08-27 22:32:13','2014-08-27 22:32:13','',23,'http://localhost/2014/08/23-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(77,1,'2014-08-27 22:35:34','2014-08-27 22:35:34','In the US alone, consumers spent over $4.6 billion on games and related accessories in the first quarter of 2014 <a title=\"NPD Group Post\" href=\"https://www.npd.com/wps/portal/npd/us/news/press-releases/npd-total-industry-consumer-spending-on-video-games-at-4-billion-for-q1-2014/\" target=\"_blank\">[1]</a>. Across Europe, 25% of all people play games at least once a week <a title=\"ISFE\" href=\"http://www.isfe.eu/industry-facts\" target=\"_blank\">[2]</a>. Despite this, gamers are frequently misrepresented. Whilst recent research shows a 48% of gamers are female, and 49% are over the age of 35 <a title=\"ESA 2014\" href=\"http://www.theesa.com/facts/pdfs/esa_ef_2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">[3]</a>, gamers are frequently considered to be predominately young males.\r\n\r\nIt\'s not just the outside world that has it wrong. Within the industry and the gaming community there are frequent frustrations about issues such as accessibility, anti-social behaviour and representation.\r\n\r\nDespite this, there is a lot of good going on in gaming. There\'s growing scientific evidence that playing games improves learning and raises self-esteem. There\'s plenty of anecdotal evidence that games can help families and friends stay in touch, as well as enabling people to cope with difficult times in their lives.\r\n\r\nThe benefits aren\'t just personal. In 2013, gamers raised over $11 million for Extra Life and Child\'s Play, with plenty of other fundraising campaigns for other charities. <strong>Gaming organisations such as guilds are often a first step t</strong>\r\n\r\nHealing Over Time is run by and for gamers, regardless of their experience level or physical location. We want to help gamers and gaming be the best it can be.\r\n\r\nWe do this by helping gamer communities to grow and aim high, enabling people to find the information they\'re seeking, tackling the hard topics and changing misconceptions about those who enjoy gaming.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"What we do\" href=\"http://localhost/what-we-do/\">Find out more.</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Our Organisation</h2>\r\nHealing Over Time is applying to become a non-profit organisation within the United Kingdom. This allows us to minimise our expenditure whilst still being as productive as we possibly can be.\r\n\r\nEveryone running and aiding the organisation is a volunteer. All staff members are passionate gamers.\r\n\r\nWe fundraise to continue and expand our work, and to support other non-profit organisations and charities. Who we support changes over time and we will always be transparent about where your money goes.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Our History</h2>\r\nThe organisation has been borne from a number of gaming communities coming together with similar interests. In December 2012, the guild Mystic Spiral ran a 24 hour gaming marathon which raised $525 for Child\'s Play. In March 2014 the first Healing Over Time event took place, with 7 guilds coming together for a joint marathon which raised $6,456 for Child\'s Play, supported by <a title=\"Supporters\" href=\"http://localhost/supporters/\">industry partners including Green Man Gaming</a>.\r\n\r\nFrom there we\'ve aimed higher and wider. We want to find others who share our vision and passion to build on what we\'ve done to see where we could go.\r\n\r\n<strong>Join our community</strong>','About Healing Over Time','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-08-27 22:35:34','2014-08-27 22:35:34','',23,'http://localhost/2014/08/23-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(78,4,'2014-06-01 11:54:03','2014-06-01 11:54:03','On the morning of the 29th of March (9am to be exact) most of the participants of Healing Over Time were already awake and gulping down their 3rd cup of coffee. Organizers were running around like headless chickens, trying to briefly fill the missing gaps before the big launch at 10am whilst trying not to panic. Volunteers placed their coolers full of goodies safely next to their computers, locking into their pilot chairs with a short prayer that their CPU’s would survive the battle of gaming that was about to ensue.\r\n\r\nWhat appeared like a fun day of games was in actual fact a series of long nights and friendly banter over the exact mechanics that would become the event itself. In short; there was a lot of planning involved; Scheduling and Website design, prize draw and distribution, getting in touch with other organizations involved, and meshing all the separate compartments into one final product, to mention just a few of the categories that went into the development of this event. But was it all successful? I think so. In the end, we not only raised our goal amount of $5000 but even exceeded this by a whopping $1456, with one main generous donations coming from the stream of <a href=\"https://twitter.com/realblankspace\">Blankspace of Viking Nation</a>.\r\n\r\nThe event itself was hosted as a means to raise donations for the charity <a title=\"Child\'s Play\" href=\"http://www.childsplaycharity.org/\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Child’s Play</em></a>, whose goal is to improve the lives of children in hospitals and domestic abuse shelters around the world via video games. As such, Healing over Time consisted of a 24 hour game-athon of a pool of 35 games including Guild Wars 2, Starbound, Minecraft, Dota2, Hearthstone, Portal 2, Titanfall, and Left for Dead 2 across 13 live streams.\r\n\r\nA brave 8 guilds stepped up to the challenge of either losing face or showing skill. Mystic Spiral [MYST] were joined by Viking Nation, Enigma, Relics of Orr, Afterlife, Dragon Season, Subterfuge Gaming, and BOON Control. Some of us had live streams to involve the audience in our epic quest, which grew steadily more entertaining as the hours flew by and fatigue set in. To add to the list streamers were capped at PG-13 which was probably the biggest challenge, especially after the 15 hour mark.\r\n\r\nCursing aside, each streamer received a colourful variety of prizes, which were handed out when questions were posed to the viewers or were added to a post-event prize draw as donations reached certain milestones. These prizes included; Guild Wars 2 items from a mouse mat to a hoodie and even some toasters (one of which made it as far as Brazil) to game codes, and vouchers for Green Man Gaming.\r\n\r\nIt was an all-around engaging event to be a part of, where doing what we love allowed us to assist a worthy cause. Given the chance most, if not all, of us would do it all over again, for both the experience and the charity.','Healing Over Time Spring 2014 Roundup','','publish','open','open','','healing-over-time-spring-2014-roundup','','','2014-08-28 22:15:46','2014-08-28 22:15:46','',0,'http://localhost/?p=78',0,'post','',0),(79,1,'2014-08-28 22:05:06','2014-08-28 22:05:06','On the morning of the 29th of March (9am to be exact) most of the participants of Healing Over Time were already awake and gulping down their 3rd cup of coffee. Organizers were running around like headless chickens, trying to briefly fill the missing gaps before the big launch at 10am whilst trying not to panic. Volunteers placed their coolers full of goodies safely next to their computers, locking into their pilot chairs with a short prayer that their CPU’s would survive the battle of gaming that was about to ensue.\r\nWhat appeared like a fun day of games was in actual fact a series of long nights and friendly banter over the exact mechanics that would become the event itself. In short; there was a lot of planning involved; Scheduling and Website design, prize draw and distribution, getting in touch with other organizations involved, and meshing all the separate compartments into one final product, to mention just a few of the categories that went into the development of this event. But was it all successful? I think so. In the end, we not only raised our goal amount of $5000 but even exceeded this by a whopping $1456, with one main generous donations coming from the stream of <a href=\"https://twitter.com/realblankspace\">Blankspace of Viking Nation</a>.\r\nThe event itself was hosted as a means to raise donations for the charity <a title=\"Child\'s Play\" href=\"http://www.childsplaycharity.org/\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Child’s Play</em></a>, whose g